WEBVTT

00:40.974 --> 00:43.007
♪ ♪

00:53.085 --> 00:55.360
<i> (birds chirping faintly)</i>

00:57.430 --> 00:59.397
<i> (quiet chatter)</i>

00:59.432 --> 01:02.664
♪ A lot of people ain't got
no supper tonight ♪

01:02.699 --> 01:04.897
("Justice Tonight/Kick It Over"
by The Clash playing)

01:04.932 --> 01:10.001
♪ A lot of people gonna
have to stand up and fight ♪

01:10.036 --> 01:11.838
♪ It's your action ♪

01:11.873 --> 01:13.147
(scatting)

01:13.182 --> 01:15.248
♪ Your action... ♪

01:15.283 --> 01:18.449
(lyrics fading)

01:25.150 --> 01:27.590
<i> -(students chattering)</i>
-MAN:<i> All right, come on.</i>

01:27.625 --> 01:29.526
<i> -(clapping)</i>
<i> -All right.</i>

01:29.561 --> 01:31.363
All right, everybody,
settle down.

01:31.398 --> 01:32.661
-(students shushing)
-All right.

01:32.696 --> 01:35.169
Welcome to first day of school.

01:35.204 --> 01:38.964
My name is Mr. Turkeltaub.

01:38.999 --> 01:40.933
(students laughing)

01:40.968 --> 01:43.034
Mr. Turkeltaub.

01:43.069 --> 01:46.378
You are in sixth grade now,
which means

01:46.413 --> 01:49.381
every one of you
has added responsibility.

01:49.416 --> 01:51.977
So, up here on the board,

01:52.012 --> 01:54.386
every day, I am going
to write down your homework

01:54.421 --> 01:56.388
and your assignments

01:56.423 --> 01:58.654
and the due date.

01:58.689 --> 02:00.359
You're going to be responsible

02:00.394 --> 02:02.757
because you're the leaders
of this school.

02:03.595 --> 02:05.331
Okay, then.

02:05.366 --> 02:07.564
Time for attendance.

02:07.599 --> 02:09.566
Jennifer Ashkenazi.

02:09.601 --> 02:11.095
JENNIFER:
Here.

02:12.197 --> 02:13.570
MR. TURKELTAUB:
Keith Breslow.

02:13.605 --> 02:14.901
-KEITH: Here.
-(student chuckles)

02:14.936 --> 02:16.639
MR. TURKELTAUB:
Michelle Chen.

02:16.674 --> 02:18.641
-MICHELLE: Here.
-MR. TURKELTAUB: Sharon Cohen.

02:18.676 --> 02:19.642
STUDENT (whispers):
Let me see.

02:19.677 --> 02:20.742
SHARON:
Here.

02:20.777 --> 02:22.810
-(quiet laughter)
-All right.

02:22.845 --> 02:24.911
Hey, hey, hey.
All right, give me that.

02:24.946 --> 02:27.452
Give me that right now, you.
Yeah, you.

02:35.264 --> 02:37.121
(clicks tongue)

02:38.124 --> 02:40.058
Who did this?

02:40.093 --> 02:42.060
(laughter)

02:42.095 --> 02:44.128
Who did this?

02:46.473 --> 02:48.704
Hmm?

02:49.608 --> 02:52.279
No one admits to it,
there's no gym.

02:52.314 --> 02:54.281
(students gasping softly,
murmuring)

02:54.316 --> 02:56.107
One.

02:58.287 --> 03:00.144
Two.

03:02.753 --> 03:04.423
Ah.

03:04.458 --> 03:06.359
Thought it might be you.

03:06.394 --> 03:07.888
What's your name?

03:09.331 --> 03:11.496
Paul Graff.

03:20.474 --> 03:23.002
You think this is appropriate?

03:24.643 --> 03:26.841
I'm asking you a question.

03:28.141 --> 03:29.613
(sighs)

03:29.648 --> 03:32.616
I just wanted to make
everyone laugh.

03:33.355 --> 03:34.651
Oh.

03:34.686 --> 03:36.114
Comedian, huh?

03:36.149 --> 03:38.853
You want to be Mr. Popularity,
is that it?

03:39.691 --> 03:42.494
Okay. Stand up there, in front.

03:42.529 --> 03:44.529
Go on.

03:48.634 --> 03:50.260
Joanne Darsch.

03:50.295 --> 03:51.701
JOANNE:
Here.

03:53.540 --> 03:55.441
Jonathan Davis.

03:55.476 --> 03:58.477
The name's Bond. James Bond.

03:58.512 --> 04:00.006
(laughter)

04:00.041 --> 04:01.579
MR. TURKELTAUB:
Jonathan Davis!

04:01.614 --> 04:04.142
Jonathan Davis,
get down here right now!

04:04.177 --> 04:07.079
We're gonna have order
in this classroom this year.

04:07.114 --> 04:09.455
You're back for
a repeat performance, I see.

04:09.490 --> 04:12.788
No wonder it's your second time
through sixth grade with me,

04:12.823 --> 04:14.625
'cause you got nothing up here.

04:14.660 --> 04:17.287
JOHNNY:
Look who taught me.

04:17.322 --> 04:18.695
Animal.

04:18.730 --> 04:20.125
(chiming over intercom)

04:20.160 --> 04:22.127
MAN (over intercom):
Good morning, students.

04:22.162 --> 04:23.799
This is Principal Sebell.

04:23.834 --> 04:25.933
-Would you all please rise...
-(laughing)

04:25.968 --> 04:29.035
Exchange one ten for ten ones.

04:29.070 --> 04:30.938
Class, exchange

04:30.973 --> 04:33.380
-one ten for ten ones.
-CLASS: One ten for ten ones.

04:33.415 --> 04:36.482
And that is how you subtract
large numbers, right?

04:36.517 --> 04:38.044
Sub-traction. Yeah.

04:38.079 --> 04:39.881
Mr. Turkeytaub,
I don't understand...

04:39.916 --> 04:42.554
Turkeltaub. I just explained it
to you, Mister, uh...

04:42.589 --> 04:43.885
Edgar Romanelli.

04:43.920 --> 04:45.282
Mr. Romanelli,
were you not listening?

04:45.317 --> 04:47.394
All right, you just
repeat it to yourself.

04:47.429 --> 04:49.858
-You'll learn it.
-(students laughing)

04:49.893 --> 04:52.223
I have eyes in the back
of my head, Mr. Davis.

04:52.258 --> 04:54.060
I didn't even do anything.

04:54.095 --> 04:56.469
MR. TURKELTAUB: I will not
tolerate any nonsense.

04:56.504 --> 04:59.373
Cut it out, or you will go
to Principal Sebell's office.

04:59.408 --> 05:01.639
JOHNNY:
Damn.

05:01.674 --> 05:03.641
MR. TURKELTAUB:
Right. Now, class,

05:03.676 --> 05:05.742
-exchange one ten...
-CLASS: Exchange one ten...

05:08.208 --> 05:10.483
-Okay, it's time to get ready
for gym. -(excited murmuring)

05:10.518 --> 05:13.816
Okay, but first, you all need
to get your permission slips,

05:13.851 --> 05:17.688
okay, for a trip next week
to the Guggenheim Museum.

05:17.723 --> 05:19.250
-(excited chatter)
-All right.

05:19.285 --> 05:21.989
All right, now, everybody,
line up against the wall.

05:22.024 --> 05:24.024
Shortest to tallest. Let's go.

05:24.059 --> 05:26.697
No, no, not you, not you.
Not you two troublemakers.

05:26.732 --> 05:28.094
Gym is a privilege.

05:28.129 --> 05:30.162
Especially not you,
Mr. Disruptor.

05:30.197 --> 05:32.098
Sit back down.

05:32.133 --> 05:34.265
("Alley Cat" by Bill Justis
playing)

05:34.300 --> 05:36.135
Freeze.

05:38.612 --> 05:40.744
Continue.

05:43.485 --> 05:45.650
And freeze.

05:47.984 --> 05:50.083
Continue.

05:52.725 --> 05:54.461
Uh, Johnny?

05:54.496 --> 05:56.925
Yeah?

05:58.225 --> 06:01.732
I would've, um, said something
if you really got in trouble.

06:01.767 --> 06:03.800
Don't matter, Graff.

06:03.835 --> 06:06.099
Turkey acts like
he can see behind him,

06:06.134 --> 06:08.299
like he's got
special powers and shit,

06:08.334 --> 06:10.268
but he don't ever do nothing.

06:12.514 --> 06:13.975
What are you looking at?

06:14.010 --> 06:16.879
-Apollo mission patch stickers.
-(Paul chuckles)

06:16.914 --> 06:19.717
Whoa. That's so cool.

06:19.752 --> 06:21.488
I got the whole set.

06:21.523 --> 06:23.050
My stepbrother gave them to me.

06:23.085 --> 06:25.217
He's in the Air Force,
down in Florida.

06:25.252 --> 06:27.120
Right near NASA.

06:28.354 --> 06:31.696
("A Fifth of Beethoven" by
Walter Murphy playing outside)

06:33.832 --> 06:36.327
Turkey's still playing
that disco shit?

06:38.034 --> 06:39.396
I know.

06:39.431 --> 06:41.970
And, like, disco totally sucks.

06:43.369 --> 06:46.843
You know Kurtis Blow
or Sugarhill Gang?

06:46.878 --> 06:49.175
No, but I have a lot
of records at home.

06:49.210 --> 06:50.517
What do you got?

06:51.377 --> 06:53.850
I have The Beatles--
the Red and Blue albums--

06:53.885 --> 06:56.413
which is basically
all their best songs.

06:56.448 --> 06:59.119
I heard they might get
back together soon.

07:01.629 --> 07:04.157
You can borrow 'em if you want.

07:05.160 --> 07:07.292
-(school bell ringing)
-(students clamoring outside)

07:07.327 --> 07:09.294
PAUL:
<i> I really like your stickers.</i>

07:09.329 --> 07:10.636
JOHNNY:
<i> Thanks.</i>

07:10.671 --> 07:12.429
Can I see?

07:12.464 --> 07:13.804
I got to be careful with them.

07:13.839 --> 07:15.542
I don't want Turkey
to take them,

07:15.577 --> 07:17.038
-like he took your drawing.
-I know.

07:17.073 --> 07:20.272
But my mother,
she's president of the PTA.

07:20.307 --> 07:22.879
She could get him
in a lot of trouble.

07:22.914 --> 07:24.881
Oh, that I want to see.

07:24.916 --> 07:27.048
Turkey shitting himself
would be excellent.

07:27.083 --> 07:28.379
Yeah.

07:28.414 --> 07:30.480
You going on the school trip?

07:30.515 --> 07:31.855
I don't know.

07:31.890 --> 07:33.725
It's expensive.

07:33.760 --> 07:35.958
I could probably get
the money for you.

07:35.993 --> 07:37.894
My family's, like, super rich.

07:37.929 --> 07:41.062
We went to Big Ben last year
in England with my grandpa.

07:41.097 --> 07:43.328
-Cool.
-(chuckles softly)

07:43.363 --> 07:45.572
So, if you get
your mother to sign,

07:45.607 --> 07:47.739
it could totally be party time.

07:47.774 --> 07:49.873
Actually,
I stay with my grandma.

07:49.908 --> 07:52.040
And she don't remember nothing.

07:52.075 --> 07:54.240
(chuckling): Sometimes
she don't even remember me.

07:54.275 --> 07:55.978
-That's so weird.
-(engine starts)

07:56.013 --> 07:57.914
-Where you live again?
-Hollis.

07:57.949 --> 07:59.080
(horn honks)

07:59.115 --> 08:00.686
-Got to get on the bus.
-Oh.

08:00.721 --> 08:02.248
-Cool hanging with you, Graff.
-Yeah.

08:02.283 --> 08:04.558
-Uh, see you later.
-See you tomorrow. Ten-hut!

08:04.593 --> 08:06.758
See you.

08:06.793 --> 08:08.826
♪ ♪

08:08.861 --> 08:11.455
(indistinct chatter)

08:30.311 --> 08:32.245
Ted?

08:32.280 --> 08:34.819
Ma? Dad?

08:43.830 --> 08:46.094
♪ ♪

09:07.656 --> 09:09.381
Hey, Turkey.

09:09.416 --> 09:11.889
Hey, Turkey, I'm heavyweight
champion of the world.

09:11.924 --> 09:13.792
(grunting)

09:13.827 --> 09:15.992
MUHAMMAD ALI:
<i> I am the greatest!</i>

09:16.027 --> 09:17.664
(Paul imitates roaring crowd)

09:17.699 --> 09:20.931
PAUL:
I am the greatest!

09:20.966 --> 09:23.131
X-ray vision.

09:23.166 --> 09:25.496
-(mimics weapon blasting)
-(door opens)

09:25.531 --> 09:27.773
-MAN: Hello.
-(door closes)

09:27.808 --> 09:29.170
PAUL:
Grandpa.

09:29.205 --> 09:31.238
-Hey, young man.
-Hey. Hey, Grandpa.

09:31.273 --> 09:32.976
-Hugga-mugga. (chuckles)
-(Paul grunts)

09:33.011 --> 09:34.681
♪ Tumbalalaika, tumba... ♪

09:34.716 --> 09:36.078
How you doing? Okay?

09:36.113 --> 09:37.343
-Good.
-Good.

09:37.378 --> 09:39.510
-So, check this baby out.
-What's that?

09:39.545 --> 09:40.852
-New one?
-It's... Yeah.

09:40.887 --> 09:44.185
Captain United.
I made my own superhero.

09:44.220 --> 09:45.956
Hey.

09:47.157 --> 09:49.190
-Hey, that's great.
-(chuckles)

09:49.225 --> 09:51.456
Flying high over the city.

09:51.491 --> 09:52.798
Hey, you're good.

09:52.833 --> 09:54.701
This is really impressive.
You know that?

09:54.736 --> 09:56.527
-Thank you, my good man.
-Good for you.

09:56.562 --> 09:57.704
-(chuckles)
-Good for y...

09:57.739 --> 09:59.035
That's wonderful.

09:59.070 --> 10:00.300
Uh, oh, by the way,

10:00.335 --> 10:02.533
-I got some jelly beans.
-Oh.

10:02.568 --> 10:04.436
-Shh. Okay?
-Mm-hmm.

10:04.471 --> 10:05.844
(Grandpa chuckles)

10:05.879 --> 10:07.307
Ma says I can't eat 'em.

10:07.342 --> 10:08.880
-They're bad for my teeth.
-Oh, get out of here.

10:08.915 --> 10:10.541
I've been eating jelly beans
all my life.

10:10.576 --> 10:11.784
And look at my teeth.

10:11.819 --> 10:13.819
They're perfect.

10:13.854 --> 10:15.216
(chuckles)

10:15.251 --> 10:17.053
-Hey, Grandpa?
-What?

10:17.088 --> 10:19.187
I think I want to be
a famous artist when I grow up.

10:19.222 --> 10:21.189
Oh. You want to be famous,

10:21.224 --> 10:23.059
you can do what you like,
but if you're gonna be famous,

10:23.094 --> 10:24.797
you got to sign
the drawings first.

10:24.832 --> 10:27.459
All the great artists
sign their work. Go and do it.

10:27.494 --> 10:29.065
Oh, yeah, I forgot.

10:29.100 --> 10:31.199
GRANDPA:
Yeah.

10:31.234 --> 10:34.807
I heard that, uh, today was
your first day at school.

10:34.842 --> 10:36.336
Is that right?

10:36.371 --> 10:37.744
Yes, indeed.

10:37.779 --> 10:40.010
-I hung out with
my friend Johnny. -Yeah?

10:40.045 --> 10:43.046
And we're going to the
Guggenheim Museum next week.

10:43.081 --> 10:45.015
-The Giggly-heim. Okay, good.
-(chuckles)

10:45.050 --> 10:46.918
Very nice. Um...

10:46.953 --> 10:48.722
I just remembered
we talked about something.

10:48.757 --> 10:51.054
What the heck was it?
We talked... Do you remember?

10:51.089 --> 10:53.056
Oh, yes. I remember.
We talked about

10:53.091 --> 10:55.091
a "going back to school"
present, yeah?

10:55.126 --> 10:57.126
Go and look in the bag.

10:57.931 --> 10:59.689
(rummaging)

10:59.724 --> 11:01.064
PAUL:
Holy cow.

11:01.099 --> 11:02.901
The rocket! You got it.

11:02.936 --> 11:04.738
-Do you like it?
-That's amazing!

11:04.773 --> 11:06.234
-Can we make it?
-Yeah.

11:06.269 --> 11:08.698
We'll go to Flushing Meadow,
and we'll launch it.

11:08.733 --> 11:10.073
First steps first.

11:10.108 --> 11:11.338
You know, they're coming over
for dinner,

11:11.373 --> 11:13.043
so, um, don't tell your mama.

11:13.078 --> 11:15.144
This is our secret project,
okay?

11:15.949 --> 11:17.784
Got it, Grandpa.

11:17.819 --> 11:20.017
-Thank you so much.
-You're welcome.

11:20.052 --> 11:23.614
PAUL (fading): This is the one
that went to the moon, Grandpa.

11:23.649 --> 11:25.121
RUTH:
Oh, my God!

11:25.156 --> 11:26.617
-G-G-Get... get it away!
-TED: It's a ham...

11:26.652 --> 11:28.223
-That thing, i-it's a rat!
-No, it's a hamster.

11:28.258 --> 11:29.620
-She's not gonna hurt you.
-In the house!

11:29.655 --> 11:31.127
-It's a rat. It's a rat!
-It's-it's not a rat.

11:31.162 --> 11:32.722
-It's a hamster, Aunt Ruth.
-Get it...

11:32.757 --> 11:34.229
-Get that thing away!
-It's from a science project.

11:34.264 --> 11:35.626
-Look, I'll put it on...
-Aah! My God!

11:35.661 --> 11:37.397
-Get it out of here!
-It's not gonna hurt...

11:37.432 --> 11:39.234
-It's not gonna hurt you.
-Get it the hell out of here!

11:39.269 --> 11:40.631
-Ruthie, please, it's just
the kids' pet. -RUTH: Stop it!

11:40.666 --> 11:42.270
I'm putting it away.
I'm putting it away.

11:42.305 --> 11:43.403
We had enough of those
growing up, Mickey.

11:43.438 --> 11:44.470
Hey, Grandpa.

11:44.505 --> 11:46.208
-Hey. How you doing?
-PAUL: Seriously?

11:46.243 --> 11:47.308
What are you reading?

11:47.343 --> 11:49.079
-What's that?
-Hey, you.

11:49.114 --> 11:51.081
-Stop.
-What's the rocket?

11:51.116 --> 11:52.643
It's for school.

11:52.678 --> 11:54.381
You mean fake school?

11:54.416 --> 11:56.119
You actually have to work
at my school

11:56.154 --> 11:57.714
and get real punishment.

11:57.749 --> 11:59.287
Ask me if I care, Ted.

11:59.322 --> 12:01.124
ESTHER: All right, everybody,
get ready for dinner.

12:01.159 --> 12:03.830
IRVING (grunts):
Well, it's not the compressor.

12:03.865 --> 12:05.722
(radio playing indistinctly)

12:05.757 --> 12:07.394
Irving, I need my oven.

12:07.429 --> 12:09.660
IRVING:
Esther, I have to fix this.

12:09.695 --> 12:11.068
What's going on here?

12:11.103 --> 12:12.564
-Hi, Dad.
-Hi.

12:12.599 --> 12:14.269
-I don't know the story.
-What's happening?

12:14.304 --> 12:15.501
IRVING:
Aaron, maybe you could...

12:15.536 --> 12:17.008
maybe you could help me
with this.

12:17.043 --> 12:18.944
I'm trying to figure out
why it's making

12:18.979 --> 12:20.737
this grinding sound.

12:20.772 --> 12:22.343
And, uh, I think maybe

12:22.378 --> 12:24.345
-the Freon... Freon lines...
-(Grandpa stammering)

12:24.380 --> 12:26.248
-ESTHER: Dad, watch your suit.
-GRANDPA: Yeah.

12:26.283 --> 12:28.921
There's a defrost timer.
Try that.

12:28.956 --> 12:31.220
-The defrost timer?
-Yeah.

12:32.322 --> 12:34.685
-What you need?
-Can you get me my socket set?

12:34.720 --> 12:36.489
-(making whooshing noises)
-(indistinct chatter)

12:36.524 --> 12:38.931
-What are you doing?
-Ow! Why'd you do that?

12:38.966 --> 12:41.032
-Because I felt like it.
-Stop, you idiot!

12:41.067 --> 12:42.363
Yeah, whatever, shithead.

12:42.398 --> 12:44.266
One, two, three, four,
five, six, seven, eight.

12:44.301 --> 12:45.531
-Um...
-PAUL: Ma?

12:45.566 --> 12:47.467
Ted pinged my ear.

12:47.502 --> 12:49.667
-Ma!
-What? I heard you.

12:49.702 --> 12:50.976
So?

12:51.011 --> 12:53.044
And you're totally innocent,
I'm sure.

12:53.079 --> 12:55.145
-Yes, I am!
-(mocking): "But I am, Ma."

12:55.180 --> 12:57.213
-Yes. I... (sighs)
-"Yes."

12:57.248 --> 12:59.380
-(Esther babbling mockingly)
-I am innocent, Ma!

12:59.415 --> 13:02.713
-(smooching)
-(Paul gagging)

13:03.925 --> 13:06.189
How was school, buster?

13:06.224 --> 13:07.322
-It was fine.
-Yeah?

13:07.357 --> 13:08.653
I have Mr. Turkeltaub.

13:08.688 --> 13:10.226
-Can you sign
a permission slip? -Hmm?

13:10.261 --> 13:12.063
We're going on a class trip
next week.

13:12.098 --> 13:14.725
-Ah.
-Into the city with my friends.

13:14.760 --> 13:19.565
Guess whose mother already
did it in my school meeting.

13:19.600 --> 13:21.072
-Ma?
-Yeah?

13:21.107 --> 13:23.173
How much power
do you have at school?

13:23.208 --> 13:26.143
Like, do you run everything
or...

13:26.178 --> 13:27.474
(snickers)

13:27.509 --> 13:28.739
(laughing)

13:28.774 --> 13:30.246
ESTHER (laughing):
No.

13:30.281 --> 13:32.919
No, I'm the president
of the PTA. Why?

13:32.954 --> 13:34.844
-Mm. Just wondering.
-Hmm.

13:34.879 --> 13:36.351
What is that?

13:36.386 --> 13:38.925
It's a type of fish.
It's very nice.

13:38.960 --> 13:40.520
It's called scrod.

13:40.555 --> 13:43.259
Well, I'm definitely
not eating scrod.

13:43.294 --> 13:45.063
Look, what does it matter
what it's called?

13:45.098 --> 13:47.197
It flakes.
That means it's fresh.

13:47.232 --> 13:48.759
-Like fresh doggy doo.
-Hey.

13:48.794 --> 13:50.200
I'll just eat the spaghetti

13:50.235 --> 13:52.763
and order dumplings
from Fan Fan for delivery.

13:53.568 --> 13:55.271
Don't you dare. Don't you dare.

13:55.306 --> 13:56.866
No, no, no, no, no, no, no, no.

13:56.901 --> 13:58.208
I have made plenty of food.

13:58.243 --> 13:59.440
You're not ordering dumplings.

13:59.475 --> 14:01.079
We'll soon see about that.

14:01.114 --> 14:02.278
Excuse me?

14:02.313 --> 14:04.115
Hey, jelly bean, come here.

14:04.150 --> 14:06.447
Eat this.

14:06.482 --> 14:08.284
Have this.

14:08.319 --> 14:09.516
Behave yourself.

14:09.551 --> 14:11.122
Don't give your mother
a hard time.

14:11.157 --> 14:13.289
-(Paul grunts)
-Now, get out of here.

14:13.324 --> 14:14.752
Tell your brother
to behave, too.

14:14.787 --> 14:16.292
PAUL:
Okay.

14:17.130 --> 14:18.558
IRVING:
Now, I like the Throgs Neck.

14:18.593 --> 14:20.065
-I like the suspension bridge.
-(slurping)

14:20.100 --> 14:21.462
ESTHER:
Don't slurp.

14:21.497 --> 14:23.299
IRVING: The Kosciuszko Bridge
is a nice bridge.

14:23.334 --> 14:24.861
-It's a comely bridge.
-Don't slurp.

14:24.896 --> 14:28.205
For me, a truss bridge
is-is the best bridge.

14:28.240 --> 14:29.635
-ALL: A truss bridge?
-IRVING: A truss bridge.

14:29.670 --> 14:31.142
I thought that's what you wear
around your back.

14:31.177 --> 14:32.979
GRANDPA:
Here. Bloody worms.

14:33.014 --> 14:36.147
IRVING: A truss bridge of,
uh, interconnected triangles,

14:36.182 --> 14:40.217
and a triangle cannot
be distorted by stress,

14:40.252 --> 14:42.879
-so it's perfectly
load-bearing. -(Ted chuckling)

14:42.914 --> 14:44.419
LOUIS: You know, we go over
the Kosciuszko...

14:44.454 --> 14:45.750
IRVING:
What are you laughing about?

14:45.785 --> 14:47.620
Your father's making
a really good point.

14:47.655 --> 14:49.325
It's perfectly load-bearing.
It's not distorted by stress.

14:49.360 --> 14:50.491
ESTHER: I actually have
a little announcement.

14:50.526 --> 14:52.295
RUTH:
Esther would like to talk.

14:52.330 --> 14:53.593
(clears throat)

14:53.628 --> 14:56.002
I've decided
with, uh, your support

14:56.037 --> 14:58.664
that I'm gonna run
for the district school board.

14:58.699 --> 15:00.666
-GRANDMA: Oh, that's wonderful.
-(clapping)

15:00.701 --> 15:01.667
Wonderful.

15:01.702 --> 15:05.011
ESTHER:
Thank you. Okay, okay.

15:05.046 --> 15:06.606
You gonna win?

15:06.641 --> 15:09.345
With your support, yeah,
yeah, I might.

15:09.380 --> 15:11.248
(chuckles) It sounds like
you're not gonna.

15:11.283 --> 15:12.942
(Ted laughs)

15:12.977 --> 15:14.680
I said I needed your support,
not rude comments, all right?

15:14.715 --> 15:16.418
Did you hear
what he said to me?

15:16.453 --> 15:19.454
Hey, don't make yourself
objectionable for once, okay?

15:19.489 --> 15:21.423
Wipe your face. Wipe your face.

15:21.458 --> 15:23.029
GRANDMA:
Esther, dear,

15:23.064 --> 15:24.921
why would you run
for the school board

15:24.956 --> 15:26.527
with Teddy in private school?

15:26.562 --> 15:28.331
ESTHER:
For Paul's sake.

15:28.366 --> 15:29.959
And to make a difference
in the community.

15:29.994 --> 15:32.632
GRANDMA: I'm sorry, I think
that's absolutely crazy.

15:32.667 --> 15:34.766
Paulie should be
in Ted's school anyway.

15:34.801 --> 15:36.207
And we can help.

15:36.242 --> 15:37.373
-Can't we, Aaron?
-GRANDPA: Yeah, we can help.

15:37.408 --> 15:38.506
GRANDMA:
Absolutely.

15:38.541 --> 15:40.046
He's fine where he is now, Ma.

15:40.081 --> 15:41.872
GRANDMA: I'm just saying
that the public school system

15:41.907 --> 15:44.710
is just not what it was
when we taught there.

15:44.745 --> 15:45.612
Am I right?

15:45.647 --> 15:47.350
GRANDPA:
It's changed, I guess.

15:47.385 --> 15:49.451
Grandma, I like school.

15:49.486 --> 15:51.222
All my friends are there.

15:51.257 --> 15:54.159
My dear boy, you will be able
to make friends everywhere.

15:54.194 --> 15:55.556
Let me tell you something.

15:55.591 --> 15:57.558
The class sizes there
are out of control,

15:57.593 --> 15:59.659
and they are now
bringing kids in

15:59.694 --> 16:01.892
from all over
those neighborhoods.

16:01.927 --> 16:03.168
The Blacks are coming in...

16:03.203 --> 16:05.368
-Ma!
-GRANDMA: I'm sorry.

16:05.403 --> 16:07.073
Come on.
They got nowhere else to go.

16:07.108 --> 16:08.503
Their schools are broken.

16:08.538 --> 16:10.076
He should be going
to private school, Aaron.

16:10.111 --> 16:12.342
-RUTH: I don't believe this.
-GRANDMA: You know that.

16:12.377 --> 16:14.377
RUTH:
These are my kiddush cups.

16:14.412 --> 16:16.412
I brought them back
from Czechoslovakia.

16:16.447 --> 16:17.842
GRANDMA:
Congratulations.

16:17.877 --> 16:19.976
You were in Czechoslovakia,
Aunt Ruth?

16:20.011 --> 16:21.351
Yes.

16:21.386 --> 16:24.255
I worked for the Pentagon
right after the war.

16:24.290 --> 16:29.194
I was relocating
displaced persons in Prague.

16:29.229 --> 16:30.921
TED:
That's so cool.

16:30.956 --> 16:33.099
Your great-aunt is
a very impressive person.

16:33.134 --> 16:35.431
I went into this
thrift store there,

16:35.466 --> 16:37.565
and I saw all these
kiddush cups.

16:37.600 --> 16:40.337
Then I looked at
the bottom of the cups,

16:40.372 --> 16:43.109
-and I saw all these names.
-Wow.

16:43.144 --> 16:45.606
I knew they were stolen
from Jews

16:45.641 --> 16:47.410
that went to the camps.

16:47.445 --> 16:49.445
-I almost fell over.
-(coughing)

16:49.480 --> 16:50.908
(Irving gags)

16:50.943 --> 16:53.944
(gasping, gagging)

16:53.979 --> 16:55.781
(Paul and Ted laughing)

16:55.816 --> 16:57.981
RUTH:
What are you laughing at?

16:58.984 --> 17:00.522
How can you laugh at that?

17:00.557 --> 17:02.128
What are you laughing at?

17:02.163 --> 17:03.525
RUTH:
How can you kids...

17:03.560 --> 17:05.560
The Nazis took 'em
to the camps.

17:05.595 --> 17:08.057
Esther, they're laughing
about Nazis.

17:08.092 --> 17:10.136
-Irving.
-RUTH: That's not funny.

17:10.171 --> 17:11.797
-IRVING: Behave.
-RUTH: What are you...

17:11.832 --> 17:13.403
-What are you laughing at?
-Behave!

17:13.438 --> 17:15.141
-ESTHER: Aah! Irving.
-RUTH: That's not funny.

17:15.176 --> 17:17.143
-That's all. Eat the meat.
-ESTHER: No, no, no, no, no.

17:17.178 --> 17:19.145
-I don't want to hear
any reasons. -IRVING: Here.

17:19.180 --> 17:21.708
ESTHER: There's no excuse
for that. I'm so sorry.

17:21.743 --> 17:23.248
You're gonna catch
your father's temper.

17:23.283 --> 17:24.909
GRANDPA:
It's not funny.

17:24.944 --> 17:27.384
I can't see why we just don't
have dumplings every night.

17:27.419 --> 17:29.287
This is disgusting.

17:29.322 --> 17:30.717
ESTHER:
It's not disgusting.

17:30.752 --> 17:32.719
And we can't have dumplings
every night,

17:32.754 --> 17:34.160
because then we'd never have

17:34.195 --> 17:35.656
a single dollar
for anything else.

17:35.691 --> 17:37.460
-IRVING: Eat it.
-You know what I teach, buddy?

17:37.495 --> 17:38.659
I teach home economics.

17:38.694 --> 17:39.924
All right?
You know what that means?

17:39.959 --> 17:41.431
It means I teach
how to stay on a budget.

17:41.466 --> 17:42.663
-All right?
-IRVING: What did I say?

17:42.698 --> 17:44.060
-ESTHER: He has no idea.
-IRVING: Eat it.

17:44.095 --> 17:45.435
ESTHER: He has no idea
the meaning of a dollar.

17:45.470 --> 17:46.733
He has no idea
how hard we work.

17:46.768 --> 17:47.800
He just...
he does not get it at all.

17:47.835 --> 17:49.604
(mock babbling)

17:49.639 --> 17:51.573
Hey, stop that. No, no.

17:51.608 --> 17:53.905
(sighs) Dumplings, suckers.

17:53.940 --> 17:57.150
ESTHER: Paul, what are you...
Don't you dare.

17:57.185 --> 17:58.811
Paul, don't you dare.

17:58.846 --> 18:00.351
-Paul, what are you doing?
-Hey.

18:00.386 --> 18:01.583
Hey, get me some fried.

18:01.618 --> 18:03.255
No. What, now you
don't like dinner?

18:03.290 --> 18:05.455
-TED: It's got all this water
in it, Ma. -No, it doesn't.

18:05.490 --> 18:07.017
TED: It's slipping
and sliding on the plate. Look.

18:07.052 --> 18:09.690
ESTHER: No, it doesn't!
It's just like Antonio's.

18:09.725 --> 18:11.021
-TED: It's not.
-ESTHER: Paul?

18:11.056 --> 18:12.660
Paul, don't you dial
that num... Irving.

18:12.695 --> 18:14.024
IRVING:
Hang up the phone right now.

18:14.059 --> 18:15.927
No ching chang cho food
tonight, okay?

18:15.962 --> 18:17.632
-ESTHER: Paul? -You stop!
Your mother made dinner.

18:17.667 --> 18:19.029
ESTHER: I am not joking
right now, okay?

18:19.064 --> 18:20.470
-Put down the phone.
-Paul, hang up the phone.

18:20.505 --> 18:21.966
-Paul, put the phone down.
-Paul.

18:22.001 --> 18:23.440
-Do not order that...
-Paul, put down the phone!

18:23.475 --> 18:25.035
-Paul?
-ESTHER: Have some respect.

18:25.070 --> 18:26.938
-IRVING: I'm warning you.
Hang it up. -♪ Hey, Mama ♪

18:26.973 --> 18:28.511
-♪ Your pasta ain't so great. ♪
-Put the phone down!

18:28.546 --> 18:29.875
-IRVING: You, too. Sit down.
-(all clamoring)

18:29.910 --> 18:31.712
You're gonna wind up with it
all over the rug.

18:31.747 --> 18:33.318
Hey, you shut up. You stop it.

18:33.353 --> 18:34.484
...one order
roast pork fried rice.

18:34.519 --> 18:35.650
IRVING:
Put down the phone!

18:35.685 --> 18:36.882
And one order fried dumplings.

18:36.917 --> 18:38.389
ESTHER:
Paul, put down the phone!

18:38.424 --> 18:40.358
-Hey, put the...
-IRVING: Oh!

18:40.393 --> 18:41.986
Goddamn it!

18:42.021 --> 18:43.526
What did I say?

18:45.024 --> 18:46.826
I am gonna rap you one!

18:46.861 --> 18:50.060
-175-23 74th Avenue.
-(others murmuring)

18:50.095 --> 18:51.336
I'm gonna get a towel.

18:51.371 --> 18:52.700
-I'm so sorry.
-LOUIS: No, don't worry.

18:52.735 --> 18:54.471
It's good.
Just a little bit of sauce...

18:54.506 --> 18:56.902
No, actually two order
fried dumplings.

18:56.937 --> 19:00.246
...if we don't do it now,
if we let this be

19:00.281 --> 19:01.643
another Sodom and Gomorrah,
that...

19:01.678 --> 19:03.216
GRANDMA:
Terrible governor.

19:03.251 --> 19:04.580
...maybe we might be

19:04.615 --> 19:06.252
the generation
that sees Armageddon?

19:06.287 --> 19:07.748
What a schmuck.

19:07.783 --> 19:08.980
ESTHER: Hey, does anybody want
the Chinese leftovers?

19:09.015 --> 19:10.850
Otherwise,
I'm gonna throw 'em out.

19:10.885 --> 19:13.182
No, no, d-don't throw 'em away.
I'll eat 'em.

19:13.217 --> 19:15.591
(sighs):
Okay.

19:15.626 --> 19:16.823
GRANDPA:
Hey, you okay?

19:16.858 --> 19:18.528
-Hmm?
-You dizzy or something?

19:18.563 --> 19:20.662
Oh. No, no, no, no, no.
I just have a headache.

19:20.697 --> 19:22.400
-You got a headache?
-Yeah.

19:22.435 --> 19:23.830
Okay. Come here.

19:23.865 --> 19:25.403
I have a knee ache,
and you got a headache.

19:25.438 --> 19:26.833
(both laugh)

19:26.868 --> 19:28.670
-Hey, let's have a dance.
-We're quite a pair.

19:28.705 --> 19:30.441
-(Esther laughs)
-(hums a tune)

19:30.476 --> 19:32.608
-GRANDPA: Fantastic.
-(both laugh)

19:32.643 --> 19:34.940
-(Esther groans softly)
-Hey, you're gonna be okay.

19:34.975 --> 19:37.547
These kids could
drive you nuts, though.

19:45.920 --> 19:47.722
(door opens)

19:47.757 --> 19:49.218
GRANDPA:
Hey, you.

19:49.253 --> 19:52.430
-Why don't you go to sleep?
-(sets book aside)

19:52.465 --> 19:54.894
Mm, can you stay with me?

19:54.929 --> 19:57.600
Oh, you know, someday
you may not want me here.

19:57.635 --> 19:59.129
That will never happen.

19:59.164 --> 20:02.968
I don't know. You're already
giving your mother...

20:03.003 --> 20:04.640
a hard time.

20:04.675 --> 20:06.510
PAUL:
Hmm.

20:07.315 --> 20:08.974
Why do you do that?

20:09.009 --> 20:10.943
Huh?

20:10.978 --> 20:12.318
(sighs)

20:12.353 --> 20:14.320
-Hey, Grandpa?
-What?

20:14.355 --> 20:17.884
Today, when you said
the spaghetti was bloody worms,

20:17.919 --> 20:20.326
-what did you mean?
-Oh, that.

20:20.361 --> 20:24.154
Well, my mother, you know,
when we came over here,

20:24.189 --> 20:28.059
uh, to America,
through Ellis Island,

20:28.094 --> 20:31.502
uh, they served spaghetti there
on Ellis Island.

20:31.537 --> 20:33.669
And my mother thought
it was, uh, worms.

20:33.704 --> 20:37.167
She said, "Ach, they just...
worms, bloody worms."

20:37.202 --> 20:40.577
So she wouldn't have it
in the house.

20:40.612 --> 20:42.513
Yeah, I could see that.

20:42.548 --> 20:45.175
But then why'd she come here?

20:47.212 --> 20:50.015
'Cause they wanted to kill her.
That's why.

20:50.985 --> 20:52.820
Who would?

20:53.559 --> 20:55.988
Uh...

20:56.023 --> 20:59.431
she was born and raised
in a small town

20:59.466 --> 21:02.159
called Ostropil
in, uh, the Ukraine.

21:02.194 --> 21:04.799
And her parents had a store
there in the main street.

21:04.834 --> 21:07.032
It was a shop, and, uh...

21:07.067 --> 21:08.869
But there were troops
of soldiers

21:08.904 --> 21:10.706
in the garrison who were drunk

21:10.741 --> 21:15.040
and Cossacks who were crazy,
always were.

21:15.075 --> 21:17.108
And sometimes they'd go out
looking for Jews.

21:17.143 --> 21:20.012
They'd say,
"We're looking for the Jews."

21:21.180 --> 21:24.555
And one night,
they rode into the town,

21:24.590 --> 21:27.855
and, um, they broke into
her parents' store,

21:27.890 --> 21:31.364
and, uh, they stabbed
both of them for no reason.

21:32.400 --> 21:34.158
They stabbed both of them
to death right there

21:34.193 --> 21:36.567
in front of my mama, and, uh...
(scoffs)

21:36.602 --> 21:38.327
She was a young girl.
She was 15, 16.

21:38.362 --> 21:41.407
She told me she had nightmares
about it as long as she lived.

21:42.410 --> 21:44.839
She said you should never,
ever forget the past

21:44.874 --> 21:47.413
because you never know when
they may come looking for you.

21:47.448 --> 21:51.417
And she... she was right.

21:51.452 --> 21:53.012
Yeah.

21:53.047 --> 21:54.915
But she survived. She got away.

21:54.950 --> 21:56.851
She got out.
She left her country.

21:56.886 --> 21:59.986
She left the Ukraine,
and she was unstoppable.

22:00.021 --> 22:02.527
She got through Poland
and Denmark, I think,

22:02.562 --> 22:04.056
and then to Liverpool.

22:04.091 --> 22:07.862
(chuckles) That's where
The Beatles are from.

22:09.437 --> 22:11.294
The Beatles.

22:12.473 --> 22:15.199
Anyway, she met, uh,
my father then,

22:15.234 --> 22:18.906
and they got married
and they had me, and, uh...

22:18.941 --> 22:21.238
So she said,
"Okay, come on, let's go."

22:21.273 --> 22:24.780
And we got on the boat and we
came over here to America.

22:24.815 --> 22:27.387
The land of dreams.

22:28.654 --> 22:30.918
(speaking Ukrainian)

22:37.894 --> 22:40.125
Can you sing the funny song?

22:40.160 --> 22:41.632
Which one is that?

22:41.667 --> 22:45.537
The one that goes
"mairzy ohs" and, uh...

22:45.572 --> 22:47.473
I forgot,
but you sung it to me once.

22:47.508 --> 22:49.607
What's it... What is it called?

22:49.642 --> 22:51.873
It's, uh...
♪ Mairzy doats and dozy... ♪

22:51.908 --> 22:55.580
♪ Mairzy doats and dozy doats
and liddle lamzy divey ♪

22:55.615 --> 22:57.747
♪ A kiddley divey, too,
wouldn't you? ♪

22:57.782 --> 22:59.078
(as Jerry Lewis):
Hey, lady.

22:59.113 --> 23:01.278
(laughing)

23:01.313 --> 23:03.313
ESTHER:
Dad?

23:03.348 --> 23:04.985
Mom wants to get going.

23:05.020 --> 23:06.756
Yeah. Help me up, will you?

23:06.791 --> 23:08.725
God, don't ever get old.

23:08.760 --> 23:10.826
God. Whew. (chuckles)

23:10.861 --> 23:13.059
It's Grandpa's birthday.
You'll see him soon.

23:13.094 --> 23:15.325
Oh, don't remind me.
I feel like...

23:15.360 --> 23:18.702
-(grunts playfully) Love you.
-...200 years old.

23:20.002 --> 23:24.103
Okay, kid, and, uh,
have fun at school, all right?

23:24.138 --> 23:26.842
You take care of yourself,
and remember your past.

23:27.713 --> 23:29.339
All right.
Good night, jelly bean.

23:29.374 --> 23:30.846
Love you, Grandpa.

23:30.881 --> 23:33.046
GRANDPA:
Love you, too.

23:36.524 --> 23:38.216
Love you.

23:39.560 --> 23:41.857
♪ ♪

23:43.960 --> 23:46.356
IRVING (distant):
Good night, Aaron.

23:46.391 --> 23:49.227
ESTHER (distant): Good night.
See you Sunday for brunch.

23:53.299 --> 23:55.002
GRANDPA:<i> Sometimes</i>
<i>they'd go out looking for Jews.</i>

23:55.037 --> 23:58.005
<i> They'd say,</i>
<i> "We're looking for the Jews."</i>

23:58.040 --> 23:59.842
-(gasps)
-(dog barking in distance)

23:59.877 --> 24:01.547
<i> They stabbed both of them</i>
<i> to death</i>

24:01.582 --> 24:03.681
<i> right there</i>
<i> in front of my mama.</i>

24:03.716 --> 24:05.815
<i> For no reason.</i>

24:07.016 --> 24:09.984
<i> She had nightmares about it</i>
<i> as long as she lived.</i>

24:17.730 --> 24:19.730
IRVING:
♪ Good morning to you ♪

24:19.765 --> 24:22.161
♪ Good morning to you ♪

24:22.196 --> 24:24.900
-♪ Good morning, good morning ♪
-(rhythmic tapping)

24:24.935 --> 24:28.398
-Stop!
-♪ Good morning to you ♪

24:28.433 --> 24:32.908
♪ Good morning to you... ♪

24:32.943 --> 24:37.242
♪ Good morning, good morning ♪

24:37.277 --> 24:39.684
(chuckles):
♪ Good morning ♪

24:39.719 --> 24:40.982
(inhales deeply)

24:41.017 --> 24:43.380
♪ Rise and shine ♪

24:43.415 --> 24:45.690
♪ And don't be ♪

24:45.725 --> 24:47.593
-♪ A lug nut, lug nut. ♪
-(Paul yells)

24:47.628 --> 24:48.924
Wake up.

24:48.959 --> 24:50.090
Up and at 'em.

24:50.125 --> 24:51.421
Come on. I-I-I can't, uh...

24:51.456 --> 24:52.994
I-I got a steam boiler
to fix at 9:00.

24:53.029 --> 24:54.358
I can't hang around.

24:55.603 --> 24:56.701
Up.

24:56.736 --> 24:58.230
What do we have here?

24:59.134 --> 25:01.607
("Fairytale in the Supermarket"
by The Raincoats playing)

25:01.642 --> 25:04.467
♪ A clock, a clock, a clock ♪

25:05.470 --> 25:08.273
♪ Cups of tea are a clock ♪

25:08.308 --> 25:11.177
♪ A clock, a clock, a clock ♪

25:11.212 --> 25:13.377
♪ The times I forgot... ♪

25:13.412 --> 25:14.785
IRVING:
Holy smoke.

25:14.820 --> 25:17.447
This is real
oonga-boonga music.

25:17.482 --> 25:19.416
Who can listen to this?

25:20.155 --> 25:21.726
Another... another classic.

25:21.761 --> 25:24.256
Another sterling record
in your brother's collection.

25:24.291 --> 25:25.389
Come on.

25:25.424 --> 25:28.964
IRVING:
♪ It's time for school... ♪

25:28.999 --> 25:31.032
MR. TURKELTAUB:
Down there. Hold up the plaque.

25:31.067 --> 25:33.364
Guys, hold it up.
Hey, hey. Stop.

25:33.399 --> 25:34.904
And don't stand
so close together.

25:34.939 --> 25:37.467
Remember,
lice is not your friend.

25:37.502 --> 25:40.140
All right, hold up the sign.
Down there, hold it up.

25:42.012 --> 25:44.309
-Smile for the camera.
-STUDENTS: Cheese.

25:44.344 --> 25:45.475
(camera clicks)

25:45.510 --> 25:46.916
All right. Permission slips.

25:46.951 --> 25:48.412
Let's go. Let's go.

25:48.447 --> 25:49.985
And leave your backpacks,
everybody.

25:50.020 --> 25:51.888
You'll be here tomorrow.
Don't worry.

25:51.923 --> 25:53.659
-PAUL: You gonna come?
-JOHNNY: No, I'm good.

25:53.694 --> 25:56.387
Dude, I told you.

25:56.422 --> 25:58.257
My family's really rich.

25:58.292 --> 25:59.632
Here, take it.

25:59.667 --> 26:01.095
We're going into the city.

26:01.130 --> 26:02.833
-It'll be so much fun.
-MR. TURKELTAUB: Good.

26:02.868 --> 26:04.461
And everyone needs
to find a buddy.

26:04.496 --> 26:06.463
Find a buddy.

26:11.877 --> 26:13.943
This is your mother's
signature?

26:13.978 --> 26:15.406
My grandma's.

26:15.441 --> 26:16.847
So, if I call your home,

26:16.882 --> 26:18.475
your grandmother will say
she signed this?

26:18.510 --> 26:21.885
I don't know. We don't got
a phone right in the house.

26:22.855 --> 26:25.053
Okay. Get on the bus.

26:26.694 --> 26:28.661
Now, I want good behavior.

26:28.696 --> 26:29.926
(students clamoring)

26:29.961 --> 26:31.290
MR. TURKELTAUB:
Sit down!

26:31.325 --> 26:33.864
Right now, sit down.
That is a bus rule.

26:33.899 --> 26:35.195
Stop...

26:35.230 --> 26:37.593
PAUL:
<i> Goes down so far.</i>

26:37.628 --> 26:40.398
-JOHNNY:<i> It's like a cupcake.</i>
<i> -(Paul laughs)</i>

26:41.236 --> 26:43.104
Watch this. Pop and lock it.

26:43.139 --> 26:44.534
-(laughs)
-PAUL: Pop and lock?

26:44.569 --> 26:46.470
-MR. TURKELTAUB: Mr. Davis.
-GUIDE: Follow me.

26:46.505 --> 26:48.373
MR. TURKELTAUB: Don't make me
throw you out, because I will.

26:48.408 --> 26:50.441
-GUIDE: All right, right here.
-Get back with the group.

26:50.476 --> 26:52.047
GUIDE:
This is a good place, okay?

26:52.082 --> 26:54.643
Okay, now, uh, let's go,
everybody.

26:54.678 --> 26:57.888
Here's a little gift
from us here at the Guggenheim.

26:57.923 --> 26:59.857
They're postcards
of the artist's work

26:59.892 --> 27:01.188
who you're looking at.

27:01.223 --> 27:03.025
(laughing):
There's some for everybody.

27:03.060 --> 27:05.896
Be careful.
Everybody will get one.

27:05.931 --> 27:08.899
Careful. I'm glad to see
you're so enthusiastic,

27:08.934 --> 27:10.736
-but let's take a look here.
-(clapping)

27:10.771 --> 27:12.496
Let's take a look
at this painting

27:12.531 --> 27:15.334
by the artist Kandinsky.

27:15.369 --> 27:18.073
This painting is called
abstract art.

27:18.108 --> 27:19.305
What do you think?

27:19.340 --> 27:20.911
What do you think
"abstract" means?

27:20.946 --> 27:22.011
-STUDENT: Light.
-STUDENT 2: A lot of colors?

27:22.046 --> 27:23.980
(overlapping chatter)

27:24.015 --> 27:26.279
♪ ♪

27:45.531 --> 27:47.531
PAUL:
<i> Kandinsky.</i>

27:49.304 --> 27:51.876
CROWD (chanting):
<i> Paul! Paul! Paul! Paul!</i>

27:51.911 --> 27:54.109
<i> Paul! Paul! Paul!</i>

27:54.144 --> 27:57.079
-Paul! Paul! Paul! Paul!
-GUIDE: Paul?

27:57.114 --> 28:00.082
-(chant fades)
-Paul, you are a genius.

28:00.117 --> 28:02.612
You have a pure understanding
of the work

28:02.647 --> 28:05.450
far above anyone else here.

28:05.485 --> 28:07.518
And you'll be
a millionaire soon.

28:07.553 --> 28:10.455
Look around.
You're already famous.

28:10.490 --> 28:12.292
(cheering)

28:12.327 --> 28:15.328
-(clamoring)
-(cameras clicking)

28:16.969 --> 28:19.332
MR. TURKELTAUB:
Paul Graff.

28:20.236 --> 28:24.073
Your grandfather donated
a painting to us,

28:24.108 --> 28:26.471
and we have judged
this painting

28:26.506 --> 28:29.705
to be the greatest
superhero painting

28:29.740 --> 28:31.443
that we have ever seen.

28:31.478 --> 28:34.545
And we just happen
to have it right here

28:34.580 --> 28:37.955
for the museum's
permanent collection.

28:37.990 --> 28:40.419
CROWD:
Paul! Paul! Paul! Paul!

28:40.454 --> 28:44.555
Paul! Paul! Paul! Paul! Paul!

28:44.590 --> 28:46.755
Paul! Paul! Paul!

28:46.790 --> 28:48.592
Paul! Paul!

28:48.627 --> 28:50.935
<i> Paul! Paul! Paul! Paul!</i>

28:50.970 --> 28:53.333
<i> (chant fades)</i>

28:53.368 --> 28:55.104
Mr. Graff. What are you doing?

28:55.139 --> 28:56.633
Get back with the group.
All right.

28:56.668 --> 28:58.272
Come on. Everybody, let's go.
Let's go downstairs.

28:58.307 --> 28:59.845
Let's meet the rest
of the class.

28:59.880 --> 29:01.275
-GUIDE: Let's go, everybody.
-MR. TURKELTAUB: Come on.

29:01.310 --> 29:03.013
-Okay, kids, let's go.
-Come on.

29:03.048 --> 29:06.577
Uh, Lenore, can you please help
make sure we get everybody?

29:06.612 --> 29:07.919
Thank you.

29:07.954 --> 29:09.646
JOHNNY:
Turkey didn't do a head count.

29:09.681 --> 29:11.021
You want to split?

29:11.056 --> 29:13.254
-Right now?
-Yeah. Go wherever.

29:13.289 --> 29:15.025
-(Johnny chuckles)
-Yeah.

29:15.060 --> 29:17.027
♪ ♪

29:17.062 --> 29:18.325
Whoo!

29:19.064 --> 29:21.526
(both laughing)

29:21.561 --> 29:23.297
PAUL:
Whoo!

29:28.403 --> 29:30.271
JOHNNY (laughing):
Cops are coming!

29:30.306 --> 29:33.010
(laughing continues)

29:33.045 --> 29:34.880
Cops are coming!

29:34.915 --> 29:36.508
PAUL:
They're getting closer!

29:36.543 --> 29:40.215
Okay, so just, let's not get
into anything worse, okay?

29:40.250 --> 29:41.986
JOHNNY: It's cool.
My cousin's visiting,

29:42.021 --> 29:44.351
so I don't have to go home
and take care of my grandma.

29:44.386 --> 29:45.858
-We got the whole day.
-(woman shouts)

29:45.893 --> 29:47.057
JOHNNY:
Whoa. Watch out.

29:47.092 --> 29:48.388
MAN:
Hey, hey, leave me alone.

29:48.423 --> 29:50.291
WOMAN:
Fuck you in the ass!

29:50.326 --> 29:53.195
♪ Roller coaster of love ♪

29:53.230 --> 29:55.395
-♪ Say what? ♪
-♪ Roller coaster ♪

29:55.430 --> 29:57.232
Look, look, look, look.

29:57.267 --> 30:00.565
-♪ Ooh, ooh, ooh ♪
-♪ Roller coaster... ♪

30:00.600 --> 30:02.875
You think they're gonna know
we cut out?

30:02.910 --> 30:04.470
(scoffs) No way.

30:04.505 --> 30:07.341
Um, I just hope
they don't check.

30:08.179 --> 30:09.739
Nothing's gonna happen
to you, man.

30:09.774 --> 30:11.213
You're, like, rich,

30:11.248 --> 30:12.918
and your mother is
president of the school.

30:12.953 --> 30:14.645
Turkey ain't gonna touch you.

30:14.680 --> 30:16.449
I knew that.

30:17.452 --> 30:19.089
But what about you, though?

30:19.124 --> 30:21.421
'Cause Turkey picks on you
all the time.

30:21.456 --> 30:23.588
He don't mean shit to me.

30:26.263 --> 30:27.757
ANNOUNCER:
The Sugarhill Gang,

30:27.792 --> 30:29.231
October 6, 7, 8 at the Ritz...

30:29.266 --> 30:30.936
(chuckling):
Oh, shit. Sugarhill Gang.

30:30.971 --> 30:32.399
-I told you about them.
-Mm-hmm.

30:32.434 --> 30:34.269
You and me, we're going
to that show next month.

30:34.304 --> 30:36.568
-Cut out from school early.
-All right. I'm in.

30:37.703 --> 30:40.605
Let's go to Colony Records.
We can get the album.

30:40.640 --> 30:42.640
Oh, yeah. (chuckles)

30:48.252 --> 30:50.450
It's a tilt.

30:50.485 --> 30:51.924
Energy.

30:52.817 --> 30:54.685
PAUL:<i> I mean,</i>
<i> when you think about it,</i>

30:54.720 --> 30:57.424
it's just a bunch of lines
and shapes and dots,

30:57.459 --> 30:59.855
and you think, "Well, this guy
is, like, a dumb idiot."

30:59.890 --> 31:02.627
Which I can understand,
but it's actually super hard

31:02.662 --> 31:04.761
'cause look how he crossed
through the triangle.

31:04.796 --> 31:07.764
Look, there's, like, a moon
and then, like, a frowny face

31:07.799 --> 31:10.800
-with one eyeball.
-Oh, yeah, 'cause the eyeballs.

31:10.835 --> 31:14.309
So, this is frowny face,
and then when you flip it...

31:14.344 --> 31:15.805
BOTH:
Happy face.

31:15.840 --> 31:16.982
(both chuckle)

31:17.017 --> 31:18.478
PAUL:
Cool.

31:18.513 --> 31:21.448
And this one right here,
it looks like a spaceship.

31:21.483 --> 31:24.781
-(makes whooshing sounds)
-Speaking of spaceships.

31:24.816 --> 31:26.585
I got doubles.

31:27.423 --> 31:29.423
-You can have one if you want.
-Really?

31:29.458 --> 31:32.756
Wait, which one's the first one
with Neil Armstrong?

31:32.791 --> 31:34.065
That ain't the first one.

31:34.100 --> 31:35.825
That's 11,
with the eagle on it.

31:35.860 --> 31:37.299
It's worth the most.

31:37.334 --> 31:39.202
Really valuable. Here.

31:40.205 --> 31:42.502
-PAUL: That's so fly.
-JOHNNY: Yeah.

31:42.537 --> 31:44.504
PAUL:
Thanks so much.

31:44.539 --> 31:46.440
I walk on Mars,
they make a patch,

31:46.475 --> 31:47.936
and it's the Davis mission.

31:47.971 --> 31:49.245
I'd come with you.

31:49.280 --> 31:50.840
JOHNNY:
You know, I could do that,

31:50.875 --> 31:52.644
be an astronaut.

31:56.122 --> 31:58.221
Hey, fool.

31:59.059 --> 32:00.388
What's that game?

32:01.193 --> 32:03.754
Ain't no game. It's from NASA.

32:03.789 --> 32:05.195
NASA?

32:05.230 --> 32:07.032
They ain't gonna let
your Black ass in

32:07.067 --> 32:09.397
even through the back door.

32:10.631 --> 32:11.894
(scoffs)

32:12.864 --> 32:15.898
-Dumbass motherfucker.
-(man laughing)

32:21.246 --> 32:23.675
Fuck them, man.

32:23.710 --> 32:25.677
Yeah.

32:26.911 --> 32:28.911
They suck.

32:36.162 --> 32:38.426
(train clacking and screeching)

32:57.777 --> 32:59.414
PAUL:
Wait.

32:59.449 --> 33:01.251
Are you getting off?

33:01.286 --> 33:03.055
That's right.

33:03.090 --> 33:04.848
Do I got to have permission?

33:06.951 --> 33:08.654
Is everything okay?

33:08.689 --> 33:10.887
It's not 'cause of you, Graff.

33:10.922 --> 33:14.627
I'm just tired of taking shit
from everybody.

33:17.137 --> 33:19.269
S-Sorry.

33:19.304 --> 33:21.568
(train wheels screeching)

33:23.473 --> 33:25.770
Well, I'll see you in class.

33:26.806 --> 33:28.476
Bye.

33:34.154 --> 33:37.617
("Rapper's Delight"
by The Sugarhill Gang playing)

33:42.052 --> 33:44.019
♪ I said a-hip-hop,
the hippie, the hippie ♪

33:44.054 --> 33:46.197
♪ To the hip, hip-hop, and you
don't stop the rockin' ♪

33:46.232 --> 33:48.397
♪ To the bang-bang boogie,
say up jump the boogie ♪

33:48.432 --> 33:50.597
♪ To the rhythm of the boogie,
the beat ♪

33:50.632 --> 33:52.962
♪ Now, what you hear
is not a test ♪

33:52.997 --> 33:54.799
♪ I'm rapping to the beat ♪

33:54.834 --> 33:57.307
♪ And me, the groove
and my friends ♪

33:57.342 --> 33:59.210
♪ Are gonna try
to move your feet ♪

33:59.245 --> 34:02.312
♪ You see, I am Wonder Mike,
and I'd like to say hello ♪

34:02.347 --> 34:03.907
ESTHER: Paul?
Can you come down, please?

34:03.942 --> 34:06.316
♪ To the black, to the white,
the red and the brown ♪

34:06.351 --> 34:08.153
♪ The purple and yellow,
but first... ♪

34:08.188 --> 34:10.452
(song continues playing
in distance)

34:12.115 --> 34:13.983
Hey.

34:14.018 --> 34:15.622
Have a seat.

34:16.757 --> 34:19.989
What's up? Everything cool?

34:20.024 --> 34:22.497
ESTHER:
Hmm. So...

34:22.532 --> 34:25.302
-it's Grandpa's birthday.
-Hi.

34:25.337 --> 34:27.172
But he got you a present.

34:27.207 --> 34:29.339
'Cause he's always
thinking of you.

34:29.374 --> 34:30.670
What is it?

34:30.705 --> 34:32.276
GRANDPA:
Well, have a look.

34:32.311 --> 34:34.102
Open it up.

34:34.137 --> 34:36.676
And be careful, 'cause
they can make quite a mess.

34:36.711 --> 34:38.414
We'd be in big trouble.

34:38.449 --> 34:41.010
I had a set just like that
when I was your age.

34:41.045 --> 34:42.880
(Grandpa chuckles)

34:47.392 --> 34:50.789
Holy cow.

34:50.824 --> 34:53.924
Thank you so much, my good man.

34:53.959 --> 34:55.959
It's-it's like a set
for professionals.

34:55.994 --> 34:58.533
Well, you want to be
a professional, don't you?

34:58.568 --> 35:01.173
Well, let's say it's very good
to have as a hobby.

35:02.242 --> 35:03.703
PAUL:
Hey, Grandpa.

35:03.738 --> 35:06.706
Now we really need
to get you something.

35:06.741 --> 35:08.543
No, no. Seeing you is
my birthday present.

35:08.578 --> 35:10.039
How about that?

35:10.844 --> 35:12.547
ESTHER:
Go put your shoes on.

35:12.582 --> 35:14.285
We're gonna go to the
Sly Fox Inn and then a movie.

35:14.320 --> 35:15.682
GRANDPA:
Yeah. What are we gonna see?

35:15.717 --> 35:16.881
♪ ♪

35:16.916 --> 35:18.223
LOUIS: Wait for me,
wait for me, wait for me.

35:18.258 --> 35:19.455
ESTHER:
Oh, here we go.

35:19.490 --> 35:20.819
IRVING:
She's really something.

35:20.854 --> 35:22.491
I'd like it that
she showed me her dog tags.

35:22.526 --> 35:23.987
ESTHER:
She was a liberated woman.

35:24.022 --> 35:25.890
You know, she was a JAP,
but she grew up.

35:25.925 --> 35:27.397
She was supposed to be
Japanese?

35:27.432 --> 35:28.827
See, I didn't get that.

35:28.862 --> 35:30.400
No, Lobby, she was
a Jewish American princess.

35:30.435 --> 35:32.237
I never heard of that
in all my life.

35:32.272 --> 35:33.733
Oh, my... Lobby.

35:33.768 --> 35:35.735
You'll use that paint set
I gave you, won't you?

35:35.770 --> 35:38.067
-Of course I will, partner.
-Good.

35:38.102 --> 35:40.674
Yeah, it was a good movie.
What's her name, Golda?

35:40.709 --> 35:42.412
-GRANDMA: Goldie Hawn.
-Goldie Hawn.

35:42.447 --> 35:44.513
-She was excellent.
-Yeah.

35:44.548 --> 35:45.811
(groaning):
Oh, God.

35:45.846 --> 35:47.417
-GRANDMA: What is it?
-(Ted laughs)

35:47.452 --> 35:48.748
-PAUL: Stop! Stop!
-GRANDPA: It's my leg.

35:48.783 --> 35:50.651
-Okay, okay. Enough.
-You're so annoying!

35:50.686 --> 35:52.323
-Just stop!
-Enough. That...

35:52.358 --> 35:54.083
-PAUL: He hit me first!
-RUTH: Stop, stop, stop, stop.

35:54.118 --> 35:56.151
Show me where. Show me.
Show me. I don't understand.

35:56.186 --> 35:57.856
-Is it a sharp pain,
or is it just... -Grandpa?

35:57.891 --> 35:59.561
It's down in the shins,
and I can't feel my feet.

35:59.596 --> 36:01.563
-What happened?
-I'm okay, jelly bean.

36:01.598 --> 36:03.763
-Dad? -No, it's there,
there down in the shin. Yeah.

36:03.798 --> 36:05.567
GRANDMA: We're gonna wrap it
in ice and get some...

36:05.602 --> 36:07.195
You all right? Is he all right?

36:07.230 --> 36:08.735
Whoa, whoa, big guy. You okay?

36:08.770 --> 36:10.374
-GRANDMA: I don't know.
-ESTHER: Is it your leg?

36:10.409 --> 36:12.068
-GRANDPA: Yes. -LOUIS: Have you
seen the doctor, Aaron?

36:12.103 --> 36:13.905
GRANDPA: Yeah, I saw Benzi.
He says I got arthritis.

36:13.940 --> 36:15.544
LOUIS: The car's around the
corner. I'm gonna go get it.

36:15.579 --> 36:16.776
-ESTHER: He's fine.
-You got to be careful.

36:16.811 --> 36:17.843
I'm being careful.
Stop fussing.

36:17.878 --> 36:19.548
You're all fussing around me.

36:19.583 --> 36:21.451
<i> Come on, I'm okay. I'm okay.</i>

36:21.486 --> 36:24.212
♪ ♪

36:24.247 --> 36:25.554
TED:
Where are we going?

36:25.589 --> 36:27.985
ESTHER:
We're looking at houses.

36:31.463 --> 36:33.991
People have
more money than God.

36:35.093 --> 36:36.532
Oh, see, that one I like.

36:36.567 --> 36:38.226
-That one, the Tudor style.
-IRVING: Which one?

36:38.261 --> 36:40.228
Oh, yeah.

36:40.263 --> 36:41.801
What do you think?

36:42.771 --> 36:45.101
It's a gold mine
for home improvement here.

36:45.136 --> 36:46.674
Gold mine.

36:47.479 --> 36:50.139
Our ship is coming in.

36:50.174 --> 36:52.141
You'll see.

36:54.981 --> 36:57.586
I think I want to be an artist
when I grow up.

36:57.621 --> 36:59.456
That'll make you
a ton of money.

36:59.491 --> 37:01.150
(Ted snickering)

37:01.185 --> 37:02.624
Is that true, Ma?

37:02.659 --> 37:06.155
Well, it's a very hard
industry, and...

37:06.190 --> 37:08.663
(chuckling): we don't have
a lot of contacts.

37:08.698 --> 37:10.335
IRVING:
You know what I'm gonna do?

37:10.370 --> 37:13.734
I'm gonna give you a wonderful
book by Edward de Bono

37:13.769 --> 37:16.066
called<i> The Art of Success.</i>

37:16.101 --> 37:18.805
That's the only art you need
to concern yourself with.

37:18.840 --> 37:21.445
You study something
you can fall back on.

37:21.480 --> 37:23.678
Like, uh...
like computer graphics.

37:23.713 --> 37:26.351
-ESTHER: Hmm. -IRVING: Now,
that's a growth industry.

37:26.386 --> 37:28.551
That's a job.

37:30.115 --> 37:31.983
MR. TURKELTAUB:
<i> I know how inspired</i>

37:32.018 --> 37:33.952
<i> we all were by our trip</i>
<i> to the Guggenheim</i>

37:33.987 --> 37:36.284
<i> and seeing those paintings</i>
<i> by Kandinsky.</i>

37:36.319 --> 37:41.190
So, today, we're gonna try
our very own art project.

37:41.225 --> 37:44.369
Right? So, you find a word,

37:44.404 --> 37:46.371
a word that is a noun.

37:46.406 --> 37:47.801
You all know what a noun is.

37:47.836 --> 37:49.968
STUDENTS:
A person, place or a thing.

37:50.003 --> 37:52.135
-BOY: That ends in...
-GIRL: That ends in L-Y.

37:52.170 --> 37:53.378
No, no, no. (chuckles)

37:53.413 --> 37:55.677
No L-Y. That's an adverb.

37:55.712 --> 37:57.877
So, you take a word
that is a noun...

37:57.912 --> 37:59.879
(voice fading):
and you write it out in letters

37:59.914 --> 38:02.211
made up of that exact thing.

38:02.246 --> 38:04.312
So I want you to...

38:04.347 --> 38:06.182
(laughter)

38:06.217 --> 38:08.217
-For example, books.
-Oh, my God. -Look at Johnny.

38:08.252 --> 38:11.825
Books, Mr. Davis, something
you don't know anything about.

38:12.597 --> 38:14.289
Fuck you, Turkey.

38:14.324 --> 38:16.027
-(students gasp)
-Get up.

38:16.062 --> 38:17.325
Get over there.

38:17.360 --> 38:18.568
Go on. Go, go, go.

38:18.603 --> 38:20.372
You are not doing this project.

38:20.407 --> 38:21.538
You're just gonna sit there!

38:21.573 --> 38:23.067
Fine by me.

38:23.102 --> 38:26.774
MR. TURKELTAUB: You're just
gonna sit right there.

38:32.210 --> 38:36.146
Now, all the paper should be
covered with a color.

38:36.181 --> 38:38.918
All right?
And use your imaginations.

38:38.953 --> 38:40.854
And be...

38:40.889 --> 38:43.362
-original.
-STUDENTS: Original.

38:47.467 --> 38:50.633
MR. TURKELTAUB: Color
the drawings, not the desk.

39:00.304 --> 39:02.414
(Mr. Turkeltaub clears throat)

39:03.406 --> 39:05.076
What's this?

39:06.816 --> 39:09.982
Uh, it's a Kandinsky.

39:11.117 --> 39:12.787
Stand up.

39:14.417 --> 39:16.428
All right. (sighs)

39:17.761 --> 39:20.729
Class, we went to the museum.

39:20.764 --> 39:23.292
Who saw paintings like this?

39:23.327 --> 39:25.393
I remember. That's a copy.

39:25.428 --> 39:27.296
MR. TURKELTAUB:
Now, what did I say to you,

39:27.331 --> 39:29.573
Mr. Graff, about doing
your own work here?

39:29.608 --> 39:31.069
Look, this is a copy.

39:31.104 --> 39:33.302
And it's not the assignment,
so you weren't listening.

39:33.337 --> 39:36.173
-The drawing's excellent, man.
-(students gasp)

39:37.517 --> 39:39.484
Mr. Davis, I didn't ask you.

39:39.519 --> 39:40.914
That's 'cause you're
a goddamn turkey

39:40.949 --> 39:42.817
-and I'll fuck you up!
-(students gasping)

39:42.852 --> 39:44.819
MR. TURKELTAUB: All right.
That's it! That's it! Right...

39:44.854 --> 39:47.118
Right to Mr. Sebell's
right now!

39:47.153 --> 39:49.890
-(students murmuring)
-(door opens)

39:49.925 --> 39:51.859
(door bangs shut)

39:52.697 --> 39:56.567
MR. TURKELTAUB:
These are Cuisenaire rods.

39:56.602 --> 39:58.360
Okay?

39:59.836 --> 40:03.002
Okay, so now you put
the green rod

40:03.037 --> 40:07.336
on the number six row
with the "A" column.

40:07.371 --> 40:10.581
Okay? Green rod, number six row.

40:10.616 --> 40:13.452
I need a piece of graph paper.

40:14.554 --> 40:16.587
Forget it.
You're too far behind now.

40:16.622 --> 40:20.184
You can either sit quietly
or clean up the paintbrushes.

40:20.219 --> 40:21.955
Up to you.

40:25.059 --> 40:26.289
Oh.

40:26.324 --> 40:28.863
Good, Mr. Davis,
helping out for a change.

40:29.833 --> 40:32.801
All right, who'd like to go on
cleanup duty and, uh, help out?

40:32.836 --> 40:35.067
Who'd like to volunteer?

40:35.971 --> 40:37.707
Oh, look, his buddy Paul.

40:37.742 --> 40:39.511
Don't take too long.

40:39.546 --> 40:41.172
-Now...
-PAUL:<i> Hey.</i>

40:41.207 --> 40:43.438
-Thanks for sticking up for me.
-Yeah, man.

40:43.473 --> 40:45.682
How'd it go with you?
Did you get in trouble?

40:45.717 --> 40:47.211
No. I was down there
for a while,

40:47.246 --> 40:48.817
and nobody even
come talk to me.

40:48.852 --> 40:50.445
-Huh.
-Not the whole time.

40:50.480 --> 40:51.886
So I just come back up.

40:51.921 --> 40:54.350
-Wow.
-Check this out.

40:55.925 --> 40:57.562
What is that?

40:57.597 --> 40:58.860
My cousin gave it to me.

40:58.895 --> 41:00.224
He said you smoke 'em,

41:00.259 --> 41:02.160
you just, like,
laugh and laugh.

41:02.195 --> 41:03.568
(both chuckle)

41:03.603 --> 41:05.394
So, you gonna do it?

41:05.429 --> 41:07.066
-Like, now?
-Yeah, man.

41:07.101 --> 41:10.201
Suck it in.
It's made of tea and shit.

41:12.370 --> 41:13.842
(whispers):
In here.

41:19.344 --> 41:20.849
(lighter flicking)

41:20.884 --> 41:23.148
Let's boldly go
where no man's gone before.

41:23.183 --> 41:25.117
(both laugh)

41:27.594 --> 41:29.319
(coughing)

41:29.354 --> 41:30.694
Try it, man.

41:30.729 --> 41:32.520
Hold it in.

41:32.555 --> 41:35.292
(both coughing)

41:38.264 --> 41:40.297
(both laughing)

41:41.608 --> 41:43.806
(chatter nearby)

41:45.073 --> 41:47.271
He went... he went... (yelps)

41:47.306 --> 41:49.614
(laughing continues)

41:49.649 --> 41:51.913
(Johnny coughing)

41:54.148 --> 41:55.345
-How dare you!
-Shit.

41:55.380 --> 41:57.622
You're a menace!
A menace, the two of you!

41:57.657 --> 42:00.152
That's unbelievable!
Go! Get out!

42:03.322 --> 42:05.124
PRINCIPAL SEBELL:
Paul, do you know

42:05.159 --> 42:07.423
what was in that cigarette?

42:09.097 --> 42:11.064
Young man, what you
were smoking is illegal,

42:11.099 --> 42:12.604
and you could go to jail.

42:12.639 --> 42:15.002
Now, is that what you want?

42:18.678 --> 42:20.337
Would you please answer him?

42:22.814 --> 42:25.947
No, obviously not.

42:25.982 --> 42:28.246
ESTHER:
Principal Sebell.

42:32.186 --> 42:34.923
I can promise you he had
no idea what he was doing.

42:34.958 --> 42:36.661
We don't have anything
like that in our house,

42:36.696 --> 42:39.422
and, uh, he wasn't the one
who brought it into the school.

42:39.457 --> 42:40.863
And...

42:42.361 --> 42:45.098
I think it's incumbent
upon the school

42:45.133 --> 42:47.397
not only to look
at class size--

42:47.432 --> 42:49.564
take a good, long look
at class size--

42:49.599 --> 42:51.533
but also who is in what class.

42:52.503 --> 42:54.338
Mrs. Graff...

42:54.373 --> 42:57.341
I know you're thinking about
running for the district board,

42:57.376 --> 43:02.049
but have you ever thought about
remedial classes for Paul?

43:03.855 --> 43:05.789
ESTHER:
Remedial?

43:05.824 --> 43:07.285
PRINCIPAL SEBELL:
Yes.

43:07.320 --> 43:09.925
It might be an option
for you and your family

43:09.960 --> 43:12.191
moving forward, because...

43:12.226 --> 43:14.556
he may be a bit slow.

43:19.002 --> 43:22.201
My son is not slow.

43:22.236 --> 43:23.840
No, sir.

43:23.875 --> 43:25.171
PRINCIPAL SEBELL:
Mrs. Graff...

43:25.206 --> 43:27.338
ESTHER:
No, I've heard enough.

43:28.077 --> 43:29.571
Get up. Time to go.

43:33.885 --> 43:36.149
(muffled, indistinct chatter)

43:37.757 --> 43:40.087
(door opens)

43:45.996 --> 43:48.194
(distorted laughing)

43:49.098 --> 43:51.527
-(door bangs shut)
-(snapping fingers)

43:53.168 --> 43:55.069
What were you thinking?!

43:55.104 --> 43:56.301
How could you do that?

43:56.336 --> 43:57.973
-Huh?
-(sighs): Oh, my God.

43:58.008 --> 43:59.909
How am I supposed to know
it's against the law, Ma?

43:59.944 --> 44:02.307
-Oh, my God.
-Besides, it's fine.

44:02.342 --> 44:03.979
You're the president
of the school.

44:04.014 --> 44:06.146
No, I'm not. I am in the PTA,
for God's sa...

44:06.181 --> 44:08.181
I don't even think
I can run for the board

44:08.216 --> 44:09.853
or anything else
after this little episode.

44:09.888 --> 44:11.756
Thank you.

44:11.791 --> 44:13.186
Okey doke.

44:13.221 --> 44:15.254
No, it's not okey doke.
Okey dokey?

44:15.289 --> 44:16.926
This is not
a respectful response.

44:16.961 --> 44:18.686
-Where did you learn
this disrespect? -Stop.

44:18.721 --> 44:20.622
-Ow!
-What?!

44:25.970 --> 44:28.267
Where did you get
that cigarette?

44:29.633 --> 44:31.006
Hmm?

44:31.041 --> 44:32.777
Did that Black boy
that was sitting there...

44:32.812 --> 44:34.570
did he give it to you?

44:34.605 --> 44:36.913
Well, you're not to associate
with him again.

44:36.948 --> 44:38.607
What do you mean? Why?

44:38.642 --> 44:40.081
I think you know what I mean.

44:40.116 --> 44:41.753
-You mean 'cause he's Black?
-S-Stop it.

44:41.788 --> 44:44.481
-I hung out with him last year,
too, if you care. -Stop it.

44:45.484 --> 44:46.725
(mouthing)

44:47.651 --> 44:49.090
It's not 'cause he's Black.

44:49.125 --> 44:51.026
All right, he could be
green or purple

44:51.061 --> 44:52.522
or orange, for all I care.

44:52.557 --> 44:56.625
The principal said
that he was held back.

44:56.660 --> 44:58.396
So?

44:58.431 --> 44:59.870
(Esther sighs)

44:59.905 --> 45:01.201
That means
he's not very bright.

45:01.236 --> 45:02.939
-No, it doesn't.
-Yes, it does.

45:02.974 --> 45:04.534
-He's super smart and really...
-(stammers) I can't with you.

45:04.569 --> 45:06.272
-You just don't know him.
-I can't...

45:06.307 --> 45:07.977
-Your father's gonna have to
deal with you. -What?

45:08.012 --> 45:09.814
Your father's gonna
have to deal with you.

45:09.849 --> 45:11.816
Why? What's he gonna do?

45:11.851 --> 45:13.279
Guess, genius.

45:13.314 --> 45:15.083
I'm done sticking up for you.

45:15.118 --> 45:16.821
Ma? Ma, wait.

45:16.856 --> 45:18.449
(thunder rumbling)

45:18.484 --> 45:20.583
Ma! Ma!

45:22.686 --> 45:24.653
ESTHER:
Irving? Irving?

45:24.688 --> 45:26.996
-Please don't.
-I need to talk to you.

45:27.031 --> 45:28.800
IRVING:
What?

45:35.534 --> 45:37.336
(lock clicking)

45:44.015 --> 45:45.740
(panting)

45:45.775 --> 45:48.215
(Esther and Irving shouting
indistinctly in distance)

45:59.899 --> 46:02.130
(footsteps rapidly approaching)

46:03.628 --> 46:05.100
(doorknob rattling)

46:05.135 --> 46:06.805
IRVING:
Open the door.

46:08.072 --> 46:09.632
I can't.

46:09.667 --> 46:11.172
Paul...

46:11.207 --> 46:13.471
(door rattling)

46:13.506 --> 46:14.945
Open the door.

46:14.980 --> 46:17.211
-You'll hit me, Dad.
-Open it up!

46:17.246 --> 46:18.674
I'm not doing it.

46:18.709 --> 46:21.050
Your mother just said
you and some Black kid

46:21.085 --> 46:22.777
were smoking drugs in school?

46:22.812 --> 46:24.812
-I didn't know what it was.
-(door banging)

46:24.847 --> 46:28.453
IRVING:
Open the goddamn door!

46:28.488 --> 46:29.894
(crying)

46:29.929 --> 46:31.654
Please.

46:31.689 --> 46:33.392
You're gonna get it, kid.

46:33.427 --> 46:35.460
You are gonna get it.

46:35.495 --> 46:37.902
-(Paul yells)
-Come here!

46:37.937 --> 46:39.134
Stop!

46:39.169 --> 46:40.971
-(Irving grunts)
-(sobs)

46:41.006 --> 46:43.171
Stop! Please stop.

46:43.206 --> 46:45.140
-The hell is the matter
with you? -Please!

46:45.175 --> 46:47.439
-(sobbing)
-Get up!

46:48.442 --> 46:50.409
Please.

46:50.444 --> 46:52.840
S-Stop.

46:52.875 --> 46:54.545
Please stop.

46:54.580 --> 46:56.481
(coughs)

46:56.516 --> 46:58.054
(whimpers)

46:58.089 --> 47:00.749
(sobbing softly)

47:04.931 --> 47:06.854
That's enough. Stop crying.

47:06.889 --> 47:09.131
Stop blubbering.

47:11.135 --> 47:12.937
The hell are you laughing at?!

47:12.972 --> 47:14.268
There's not a single
goddamn thing

47:14.303 --> 47:15.764
that's amusing about this.

47:15.799 --> 47:17.634
Get out of here, you asshole!

47:21.112 --> 47:23.211
IRVING:
Get cleaned up for dinner.

47:23.246 --> 47:26.280
And-and wash your teeth after
with the Waterpik.

47:26.315 --> 47:28.777
Your breath
is like trench mouth.

47:30.088 --> 47:31.615
I hate you.

47:31.650 --> 47:33.485
I hate this family.

47:36.160 --> 47:37.786
What did you say?

47:38.789 --> 47:40.228
Nothing.

47:40.263 --> 47:42.263
-What did you say to me?
-Nothing.

47:42.298 --> 47:43.935
What did you say to me?

47:43.970 --> 47:45.563
I said nothing. (yells)

47:45.598 --> 47:47.796
-What did you say?!
-Nothing!

47:47.831 --> 47:49.699
What did you say to me?!

47:49.734 --> 47:50.799
Nothing!

47:50.834 --> 47:52.108
-Huh?
-Nothing.

47:52.143 --> 47:53.472
IRVING:
What did you say to me?!

47:53.507 --> 47:55.947
-(thumping)
-PAUL: Aah! Nothing.

47:55.982 --> 47:58.180
Nothing. I promise.

47:58.985 --> 48:01.513
(whimpers, coughs)

48:05.354 --> 48:07.992
You made me break
the goddamn door.

48:08.027 --> 48:10.291
(panting)

48:11.195 --> 48:13.459
(crying softly)

48:17.432 --> 48:19.168
Someday he'll learn he's not

48:19.203 --> 48:21.797
the smartest kid
on planet Earth.

48:22.833 --> 48:25.438
ESTHER: I've had it
with that school, Irving.

48:25.473 --> 48:27.869
He needs a place
with real discipline.

48:29.213 --> 48:31.906
We need to send him
to Ted's school now.

48:31.941 --> 48:33.347
No way.

48:33.382 --> 48:34.909
I'm not changing schools.

48:34.944 --> 48:37.186
-Uh-uh. Sorry, buddy.
-You think that's smart?

48:37.221 --> 48:39.023
You think that's smart?
Say another word.

48:39.058 --> 48:40.519
Do it. Do it.

48:40.554 --> 48:43.456
You don't get to call
the shots around here.

48:43.491 --> 48:45.458
Okay? I call the shots.

48:45.493 --> 48:47.856
You understand me?
You understand me?

48:47.891 --> 48:49.627
I call the shots.

48:52.368 --> 48:55.336
Things are gonna be different
around here.

48:55.371 --> 48:56.865
And your friend's from hunger.

48:56.900 --> 48:59.472
You're not gonna talk
to him anymore.

49:01.080 --> 49:03.410
(whispers):
I hate this family.

49:09.847 --> 49:11.913
♪ ♪

49:18.361 --> 49:20.361
(rock taps window)

49:27.370 --> 49:29.634
Hey. Checking in on you.

49:29.669 --> 49:32.406
Hey. How-how did you know
where I live?

49:32.441 --> 49:34.474
From that chart
they had on you.

49:34.509 --> 49:36.311
It had all the information.

49:36.346 --> 49:39.611
Well... just come here.

49:42.517 --> 49:43.912
This is my clubhouse.

49:43.947 --> 49:46.420
JOHNNY: Whoa.
You could just move in here.

49:46.455 --> 49:50.556
Yeah. My dad built it for me
a couple years ago.

49:50.591 --> 49:54.923
Your dad built
this whole thing for you?

49:54.958 --> 49:57.365
-PAUL: Mm.
-JOHNNY: Wow.

49:57.400 --> 49:59.895
When he wasn't in
an asshole mood.

50:01.470 --> 50:03.734
It's got a window
and everything.

50:03.769 --> 50:06.638
Yeah, it's a good place
to hang out, I guess.

50:08.312 --> 50:10.576
What's this?

50:12.283 --> 50:14.646
Um, Johnny?

50:16.155 --> 50:20.322
M-My parents are gonna try to
send me to my brother's school.

50:21.127 --> 50:23.292
Wow. That sucks.

50:23.327 --> 50:25.426
But I'm gonna try
and get my grandpa

50:25.461 --> 50:27.560
to change their minds, maybe.

50:27.595 --> 50:29.958
Yeah, I hope he does.

50:29.993 --> 50:32.070
I hope he does, too.

50:33.062 --> 50:34.435
What about you?

50:34.470 --> 50:36.140
They sent me up
to the third floor

50:36.175 --> 50:37.702
with, like, all the retards.

50:37.737 --> 50:40.276
So I decided
I'm cutting out for good.

50:40.311 --> 50:42.146
Do my own thing.

50:42.181 --> 50:44.005
That's so cool.

50:47.010 --> 50:48.647
Yeah, so...

50:48.682 --> 50:51.012
I'll be seeing you, I guess.

50:53.687 --> 50:55.390
Hey, I'm going to that

50:55.425 --> 50:57.293
Sugarhill Gang concert
next week.

50:57.328 --> 50:58.822
You want to catch that?

50:58.857 --> 51:00.296
Next Monday night?

51:00.331 --> 51:02.661
-For sure.
-Excellent.

51:02.696 --> 51:04.663
If you're not back at school,
I'll find you

51:04.698 --> 51:06.896
at the other place
at the end of the day.

51:06.931 --> 51:08.337
What's that called?

51:08.372 --> 51:09.998
Forest Manor.

51:10.033 --> 51:12.671
Forest Manor, yeah.

51:12.706 --> 51:14.772
The show's gonna be special.

51:14.807 --> 51:16.840
Mm. Good luck.

51:18.140 --> 51:20.250
Thanks.

51:20.285 --> 51:22.186
GRANDMA:
Not too much, Aaron.

51:22.221 --> 51:24.155
Are you coming with the bagels?

51:24.190 --> 51:25.321
GRANDMA:
She's coming, Irv.

51:25.356 --> 51:26.454
She's coming.

51:26.489 --> 51:27.950
(sighing):
Okay, okay.

51:27.985 --> 51:29.688
I don't know
what everybody wants,

51:29.723 --> 51:31.987
-so you just have to choose.
-Thank you. -Beautiful.

51:32.022 --> 51:33.824
Paul, your waffles will be out
in a second, okay?

51:33.859 --> 51:36.497
TED: Of course, he couldn't eat
what everybody else eats.

51:36.532 --> 51:37.993
ESTHER:
Leave him alone.

51:38.028 --> 51:39.632
He's in a mood.

51:39.667 --> 51:41.700
You put me in a mood.

51:41.735 --> 51:44.032
Trying to make me
change schools.

51:44.067 --> 51:46.474
But I'm not going, so...

51:47.576 --> 51:49.444
RUTH:
Eat something.

51:49.479 --> 51:51.138
-I'll take some.
-IRVING: It's not bad.

51:51.173 --> 51:52.480
LOUIS:
Hey, you give me this.

51:52.515 --> 51:54.284
-Look at that. See that?
-Thank you.

51:54.319 --> 51:57.353
(speaks Ukrainian)

51:57.388 --> 52:00.389
Yes. Yes, he needs to hear it.

52:00.424 --> 52:02.556
Okay.

52:04.758 --> 52:07.022
I told your parents to do that.

52:09.367 --> 52:10.795
You did?

52:10.830 --> 52:12.236
Yes, I did.

52:12.271 --> 52:14.535
Because the game is rigged,

52:14.570 --> 52:17.340
and we want to take care
of you and your brother.

52:17.375 --> 52:19.166
That's why.

52:19.201 --> 52:20.409
Listen to what
he's telling you.

52:20.444 --> 52:21.872
I am listening.

52:21.907 --> 52:23.676
Right. I want you
to just really listen

52:23.711 --> 52:25.678
for the first time
in your life.

52:25.713 --> 52:27.977
Because what he's saying
is important.

52:28.012 --> 52:29.814
-Just listen to Grandpa.
-GRANDPA: Listen to me.

52:29.849 --> 52:31.750
When I was young,
I was a very good student,

52:31.785 --> 52:33.587
but my name was Rabinowitz.

52:33.622 --> 52:37.558
And, um,
in college after college,

52:37.593 --> 52:39.054
during the interviews,
those people,

52:39.089 --> 52:41.155
whoever the hell they were,
they would look at me,

52:41.190 --> 52:43.597
they'd smile at me,
look at me up and down, eh,

52:43.632 --> 52:45.731
like I was some kind of freak
in the circus,

52:45.766 --> 52:48.272
and then they'd say
with a big smile,

52:48.307 --> 52:50.065
"Oh, thank you. And sorry,

52:50.100 --> 52:52.243
"but we don't need any more
Spinowitzes this year.

52:52.278 --> 52:56.610
"Uh, you know,<i> danke schön</i>
<i> and auf Wiedersehen.</i>

52:56.645 --> 52:58.513
Next." Yeah.

52:58.548 --> 53:00.614
-ESTHER: That's right.
-Do you get my meaning?

53:01.551 --> 53:03.287
IRVING:
You know what he's telling you?

53:03.322 --> 53:04.585
Do you know what that means?

53:04.620 --> 53:06.290
"We have enough
Spinowitzes here"?

53:06.325 --> 53:08.721
N-No.

53:08.756 --> 53:10.426
It means they don't want
any more Jews.

53:10.461 --> 53:11.889
That's right.
They hated us then,

53:11.924 --> 53:13.858
they didn't want us,
and they still hate us.

53:13.893 --> 53:15.728
And screw 'em. I don't care.

53:15.763 --> 53:17.763
But that's why
